rs—wildlife and grasslands biologists, archaeologists, ranchers, and petroleum geologists—to illuminate a wide range of related topics: our love affair with turf and how it manifests in lawns and sports, the ecological and economic dimensions of ranching, the glory of cowboy culture, grasslands and restoration ecology, and more. His book ultimately provides the background against which we can envision a new paradigm for restoring rangeland ecosystems—and a new paradigm for envisioning a more sustainable future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGrasses. 0aGrassland ecology. 0aGrasslands. 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh  aanecdotes.  aarchaeologists.  abiography autobiography.  aconservation.  acowboy culture.  acultural forces.  aenvironmentalists.  aevolution.  agrass.  agrassland ecologists.  agrasslands biology.  agrasslands.  ahistorical habitats.  ahuman habitat.  alawns.  amodern philosophy.  anonfiction.  anorth america.  aorganisms and environments.  apetroleum geologists.  aranchers.  arangelands.  arestoration ecology.  arestore ecosystems.  ascience majors.  asustainability.  atextbooks.  aturf.  awildlife biologists.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025839640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094452740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520944527423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520944527/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY